The paper deals with computational social choice, which is a subfield of computer science that focuses on the intersection of social choice theory and computer science. The paper specifically deals with the complexity of online manipulation of sequential elections, which falls under the category of algorithmic game theory (cs.GT). The paper also uses techniques from artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and computational complexity theory (cs.CC) to analyze the complexity of the manipulation problem. Additionally, the paper involves the analysis of voting systems and their properties, which falls under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG).
